  <div class="col-md-7">
    <p> So it was at least in one of the travel magazines that Steffi brought along. Unfortunately there was not where the animals can be seen on the port of Stephens. We just drove to Port Nelson because I had seen that there was a tourist information there and hoped that we could help us there. </p>
    <p> Unfortunately it was a failure. The lady there couldn't really help me with any of my questions. Since my feet were still of the opinion to burn, we simply decided to leave the car at the harbor and walk the short piece to the water. There we sat down and hoped to see dolphins. </p>
    <p> Unfortunately we were not lucky with it either. Since Steffi can sit even less quietly than me, we decided to walk along the pier and to explore the harbor in the hope of seeing a gray dorsal fin. </p>
    <p> When we came back to the car at some point, a huge group of white kacadus greeted us in the tree above us. These made noise and practiced flying deep in the synchronous. Unfortunately, we were still on the biscuit that Steffi's new camera had the fat lint on the lens and the photos of the cacadus did not become 100% perfect. It annoyed me so much that I took the camera and hit my finger knuckle with the lens. See there. The lint was gone. Well, lucky. </p>
    <p> Since we still did not see any dolphins, we decided to take a different way back to the campsite in the hope of seeing another strip of Port Stephens Delfine. Unfortunately it didn't work there either. </p>
